@* MudBlazor provider island — "Cyber Chapel" dark theme.

   WHY A SEPARATE COMPONENT WITH @rendermode HERE.
   MudBlazor's MudThemeProvider + MudPopoverProvider + MudDialogProvider +
   MudSnackbarProvider all require InteractiveServer context for theme
   variables to flow and popovers / dialogs / snackbars to mount.

   MainLayout itself CANNOT carry @rendermode (Body is a RenderFragment that
   can't be serialized across the rendermode boundary — see Routes.razor).
   But a *child* component of a non-interactive layout CAN carry @rendermode,
   so this component sits inside MainLayout and acts as the single
   "everything interactive needs to mount below this line" anchor.  Pages
   that opt into `@rendermode InteractiveServer` get their own circuit anyway,
   and non-interactive pages (Login, Register) keep working as static SSR
   because the providers themselves only matter for interactive fragments.

   IsDarkMode="true" forces the dark palette from ServantSyncTheme.Build().
   Both PaletteLight and PaletteDark in the theme are identical dark
   schemes so static-SSR Account pages don't flash a white background.

   The navigation drawer is a custom <aside> controlled by pure CSS/JS
   (livedrawer.js + app.css), not MudDrawer, because MudDrawer's internal
   state machine can't be toggled from JavaScript in static SSR. *@
@rendermode InteractiveServer

<MudBreakpointProvider />
<MudThemeProvider Theme="_theme" IsDarkMode="true" />
<MudPopoverProvider />
<MudDialogProvider />
<MudSnackbarProvider />

@code {
    private readonly MudTheme _theme = ServantSyncTheme.Build();
}
